<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="1" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD BGCOLOR="#fff5ba" WIDTH="150"><B>Procedural History</B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">Appellees paid the deficiencies, and<BR ALIGN='left'/>claims for refunds were filed and duly<BR ALIGN='left'/>rejected. Complaints (Nos. 9686 and<BR ALIGN='left'/>9687, consolidated by Stipulation and<BR ALIGN='left'/>Order for all purposes) were<BR ALIGN='left'/>subsequently filed for tax refunds in<BR ALIGN='left'/>the district court. The Court, in<BR ALIGN='left'/>holding in favor of appellees, found<BR ALIGN='left'/>that the facts presented a complete<BR ALIGN='left'/>liquidation by Old Stockton, entitling<BR ALIGN='left'/>it to the benefits of section 337, and<BR ALIGN='left'/>its shareholders to the benefits of<BR ALIGN='left'/>section 331. The Government appeals from<BR ALIGN='left'/>that judgment.\n\nThe Government urges<BR ALIGN='left'/>on appeal, as it did unsuccessfully in<BR ALIGN='left'/>the district court, that the facts of<BR ALIGN='left'/>this case present a &quot;corporate<BR ALIGN='left'/>reorganization&quot; as that term is defined<BR ALIGN='left'/>in section 368(a)(1)(D).[3]</TD></TR>
